This paper is about improving the performance of conversational AI agents in few-shot settings through data augmentation methods. The paper focuses on intent classification, which is a common task in natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper also uses supervised and unsupervised representation learning methods, which are common in machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper uses data augmentation techniques that are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and neural networks (cs.NE).
